{{for|the bisexual slang|Bambi effect (slang)}}[[File:Fawn-in-grass.jpg|right|thumb|A [[white-tailed deer]] fawn, the species of the title character in Walt Disney's animated film, ''Bambi''.]]The "'''Bambi effect'''" is a term used anecdotally or in editorial media that refers to objections against the killing of [[charismatic megafauna]] (animals that are perceived as "[[cute]]" or "adorable", such as [[deer]] or [[dolphin]]s), while there may be little or no objection to the suffering of [[organism]]s that are perceived as somehow repulsive or less than desirable, such as spiders or an endangered [[fungus]]<ref>{{Cite book | last = Knight | first = John | authorlink = | title = Waiting for wolves in Japan: an anthropological study of people-wildlife relations | publisher = Oxford UP | year = 2003 | location = | page = 155 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=iDqxEtYjD4YC&pg=PA155 | doi = | isbn = 978-0-19-925518-4}}</ref> and other woodland creatures.<ref>{{Cite book | last = Nash | first = Susan Smith | authorlink = | title = Leadership and the E-Learning Organization | publisher = Texture | year = 2006 | location = | page = 222 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=tMz_7-gHzX0C&pg=PT222 | doi = | isbn = 978-0-9712061-6-8}}</ref>
Referring to a form of purported [[anthropomorphism]],<ref>{{Cite book | last = Petersen | first = Hanne | authorlink = |author2=Birger Poppel | title = Dependency, autonomy, sustainability in the Arctic | publisher = Ashgate | year = 1999 | location = | page = 286 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=UudOAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Bambi+effect%22&dq=%22Bambi+effect%22| doi = | isbn = 978-1-84014-701-8}}</ref> the term is inspired by Walt Disney's animated film ''[[Bambi]]'', where an emotional high point is the death of the lead character's mother at the hands of the film's antagonist, a [[hunting|hunter]] known only as "[[Human|Man]]".<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |title=The Bambi Effect |url=http://www.portlandmercury.com/portland/Content?oid=32269&category=22127 |quote=This is the Bambi Effect: our adverse reaction to cute critters being harmed. |publisher=[[Portland Mercury]] |date= |accessdate=2007-09-25 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |title=Anti-hunting sentiment on the wane. |url=http://www.zwire.com/site/tab2.cfm?newsid=14062217&BRD=2553&PAG=461&dept_id=506066&rfi=6 |quote=Remarking on the "Bambi Effect," noted <!-- noted by whom? --> demographer Diane Crispell wrote: "Ever since (the Walt Disney classic movie) ''Bambi'', hunters have been typecast in the media as villains who take shots at anything that moves for the sheer love of killing." |publisher=[[Times Community Newspapers]] |date= |accessdate=2007-09-25 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060423204000/http://www.zwire.com/site/tab2.cfm?newsid=14062217&BRD=2553&PAG=461&dept_id=506066&rfi=6 |archivedate=2006-04-23 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | last = Boardman | first = Robert | authorlink = |author2=Debora VanNijnatten | title = Canadian environmental policy: context and cases | publisher = Oxford UP | year = 2002 | location = | pages = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=AHeuAAAAIAAJ&q=%22Bambi+effect%22&dq=%22Bambi+effect%22| doi = | isbn = }}</ref>
==Effects== Some commentators{{Who|date=August 2010}} have credited this purported effect with increasing public awareness of the dangers of [[pollution]], for instance in the case of the fate of [[sea otter]]s after the [[Exxon Valdez oil spill|''Exxon Valdez'' oil spill]],<ref>{{Cite book | last = Keeble | first = John | authorlink = | title = Out of the channel: the Exxon Valdez oil spill in Prince William Sound | publisher = Eastern Washington UP | year = 1999 | location = | pages = 4, 164 | url = | doi = | isbn = 978-0-910055-53-6}}</ref> and in the public interest in scaring birds off airfields in non-lethal ways.<ref name="davenport">{{Cite book | last = Davenport | first = Julia L. | authorlink = | title = The ecology of transportation: managing mobility for the environment | publisher = Springer | year = 2006 | location = | page = 28 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=9o7rq6WnSXEC&pg=PT28 | doi = | isbn = 978-1-4020-4503-5}}</ref> In the case of [[invasive species]], perceived cuteness may help thwart efforts to eradicate non-native intruders, such as the white [[fallow deer]] in [[Point Reyes]], California.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Slobig | first = Zachary | title = Easy Target: There's a plan afoot to eradicate the white fallow deer in Point Reyes – but could there be another way to keep rangers, ranchers, animal lovers, Hindus and venison diners on the same side? | newspaper = [[San Francisco Chronicle]] | pages = | publisher = | date = 2007-05-06 | url = http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2007/05/06/CMG2TP64HN1.DTL | accessdate = 2009-12-01}}</ref> The effect is also cited as the anthropomorphic quality of modern cinema: most people in modern [[Western civilization]] are not familiar with wildlife, other than "through TV or cinema, where fuzzy little critters discuss romance, self-determination and loyalty like pals over a cup of coffee", which has led to influences on public policy and the image of businesses cast in movies as polluting or otherwise harming the environment.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Polakovich | first = Gary | title = Column One: Seeing a Greener Big Screen; ''Erin Brockovich'' has plenty of company as films increasingly cast polluters as the villain. But businesses call the depictions slanted and say firms do their part for the environment | newspaper = [[Los Angeles Times]] | page = A.1 | publisher = | date = 2001-03-27 | url = http://articles.latimes.com/2001/mar/27/news/mn-43263?pg=5 | accessdate = 2009-12-01}}</ref>
The effect was also cited in the events following record snowfall in the U.S. state of [[Colorado]] in 2007, when food for [[mule deer]], [[pronghorn]]s, and [[elk]] became so scarce that they began to starve; the Colorado Department of Wildlife was inundated with requests and offers to help the animals from citizens, and ended up spending almost $2 million feeding hungry wildlife.<ref>{{Cite book | last = Irvine | first = Leslie | authorlink = | title = Filling the Ark: Animal Welfare in Disasters | publisher = Temple UP | year = 2009 | location = | page = 128 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=XrTy8mnCSfYC&pg=PT128 | doi = | isbn = 978-1-59213-834-0}}</ref> Among some [[butcher]]s, the Bambi effect (and in general, Walt Disney's anthropomorphic characters) is credited with fueling the [[Vegetarianism|vegetarian]] movement;<ref>{{Cite web | last = Janssens | first = Emke | authorlink = | title = Meepraten: Bambi-effect | work = | publisher = Slagerswereld | date = 2008-11-21 | url = http://www.slagerswereld.nl/meepraten/bambi-effect-(924).html | doi = | accessdate = 2009-12-01}}</ref> [[chef]]s use the term to describe customers' lack of interest in, for instance, whole fish: "It's the Bambi effect – [customers] don't want to see eyes looking at them".<ref>{{Cite news | last = Beale | first = Lewis | title = Turkeys on the menu: Chefs recall dishes they love – but customers hate | newspaper = [[New York Daily News]] | pages = | publisher = | date = 2004-04-02 | url = http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/lifestyle/2000/04/02/2000-04-02_turkeys_on_the_menu__chefs_r.html | accessdate = 2009-12-01}}</ref>
==Human attraction== A secondary meaning is sometimes found in [[psychology]], where the term may be used to refer to a perceived tendency in "humans...to find animals attractive that have characteristics similar to those [of] human babies".<ref>{{Cite book | last = Petrinovich | first = Lewis | authorlink = | title = Darwinian Dominion: Animal Welfare and Human Interests | publisher = MIT Press | year = 2001 | location = | page = 387 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=vIOXl0RHRA4C&pg=PA387 | doi = | isbn = 978-0-262-66121-8}}</ref> It is also claimed that this tendency is at work in [[human sexuality]],<ref>{{Cite book | last = Cook | first = Mark | authorlink = |author2=Robert McHenry | title = Sexual attraction | publisher = Pergamon Press | year = 1978 | location = | page = 44 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=luWFAAAAIAAJ&q=%22Bambi+effect%22&dq=%22Bambi+effect%22| doi = | isbn = 978-0-08-022231-8}}</ref> since, according to some studies,<ref>{{Cite book | last = Geer | first = James | authorlink = |author2=Julia Heiman|author3=Harold Leitenberg | title = Human sexuality | publisher = Prentice-Hall | year = 1984 | location = | page = 196 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=-ywEAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Bambi+effect%22&dq=%22Bambi+effect%22| doi = | isbn = }}</ref> most people prefer 'babylike' features in their sexual partners, that is, "a large rounded forehead, large eyes, and rounded features".
